int SetGravityType (GRAVITY_TYPE type)
 This function is used to set the gravity type: MANUAL_INPUT or OPTIMAL. The Manual mode is used by default and consists of specifying each robot link mass and center of mass. Default parameters are provided and can be changed with the function SetManualInputParam(). The second option is the optimal mode where the gravity parameters are accurately estimated by placing the robot in various positions. The precision of the Optimal mode is normally 3 times better than the manual mode. These parameters can be set with the function SetOptimalZParam (). The function RunGravityZEstimationSequence() will run a sequence of points in order to identify the gravity parameters and will output the parameters to send with the function SetOptimalZParam (). For now, this mode only works when the robot is standing (G = [0;0;-9.81]). More...

int SetSwitchThreshold (float Command[COMMAND_SIZE])
 When switching from position to torque control, the controller verifies if the torque command is close to the actual measured torque (as a safety feature to prevent high velocity motions if it is not the case). This function can be used to change the threshold over which the switching to torque mode is rejected. Default parameters can be found in the torque control documentation page under the section “Default parameters”. The parameters will reset to default values every time the robotic arm is rebooted. int SetTorqueInactivityType (int type)
 This function manages the torque inactivity time option. If not torque command is sent after a given time (250ms by default), the controller will take an action: (0): The robot will return in position mode (1): The torque commands will be set to zero. By default, option (1) is set for Kinova classic robots (Jaco2 and Mico) while option (0) is set for generic mode. More...

int SetTorqueRobotProtection (int protectionLevel)
 This function is used to activate/deactivate the robot protection zone. There are several situations where the robot can come in contact with itself. To prevent collisions that could damage the robot, a basic robot protection zone covering the majority of collisions is implemented. In a first zone around the robot’s base, the damping is increased to reduce the robot velocity. If the end-effector reaches a second smaller zone around the robot’s base, the robot will stop and return in position control. The possible values are 0, 1 and 2. 0: The protection is deactivated 1: There is some damping when the effector enter the protected zone 2: There is some damping when the effector enters the protected zone and if the effector continues in that direction, the robot will switch back in position mode. More...
 
int SetTorqueSafetyFactor (float factor)
 This function is a safety feature used to specify the velocity threshold over which the robot will stop and return to position control. This is a safety feature to prevent the arm to perform undesired and dangerous motions when implementing or using a program. The value varies between 0 and 1. A value of “0.1” means that the safety will trigger if an actuator reaches 10% of its maximal speed. If a value of “1” is set, the safety feature is disabled. The user must be very cautious if he chooses to increase the safety factor. More...
 
int SetTorqueStaticFriction (float Command[COMMAND_SIZE])

 This function sets the filter for the estimation of the velocity used for the maximum velocity safety feature. The parameters will reset to default values every time the robotic arm is rebooted. More...
 
int SetTorqueVibrationController (float level)
 This function is used to set the vibration observer/controller level. In different situations, for example when interacting with a stiff environment, vibrations may occur. The vibration observer/controller is implemented to eliminate these vibrations. The input value varies between 0 and 1. A value of “0” means that the feature is deactivated and a value of “1” means that the Vibration Observer/Controller is set to its maximal level. The observer analyzes all actuators velocity signal. If the velocity signal frequency and amplitude is too high, the controller will reduce the control gains thus reducing the vibrations. More...
 
int SetTorqueZero (int ActuatorAdress)
 This function sets the current position of a specific actuator as a torque zero. Mainly used for calibration. More...

int GetCodeVersion ( int  Response[CODE_VERSION_COUNT])

This function returns the code version of the robotical arm's firmware. The elements of the array or ordered as:

  • 0 DSP firmware's version
  • 1 DSP firmware's major
  • 2 DSP firmware's minor
  • 3 Actuator 1's firmware version
  • 4 Actuator 1's firmware major
  • 5 Actuator 1's firmware minor
  • 6 Actuator 2's firmware version
  • 7 Actuator 2's firmware major
  • 8 Actuator 2's firmware minor
  • 9 Actuator 3's firmware version
  • 10 Actuator 3's firmware major
  • 11 Actuator 3's firmware minor
  • 12 Actuator 4's firmware version
  • 13 Actuator 4's firmware major
  • 14 Actuator 4's firmware minor
  • 15 Actuator 5's firmware version
  • 16 Actuator 5's firmware major
  • 17 Actuator 5's firmware minor
  • 18 Actuator 6's firmware version
  • 19 Actuator 6's firmware major
  • 20 Actuator 6's firmware minor
  • 21 Finger 1's firmware version
  • 22 Finger 1's firmware version
  • 23 Finger 1's firmware version
  • 24 Finger 2's firmware version
  • 25 Finger 2's firmware version
  • 26 Finger 2's firmware version
  • 27 Finger 3's firmware version
  • 28 Finger 3's firmware version
  • 29 Finger 3's firmware version
  • 30 DSP firmware's iteration
  • 31 CAN interface 1 firmware's version
  • 32 CAN interface 1 firmware's major
  • 33 CAN interface 1 firmware's minor
  • 34 CAN interface 2 firmware's version
  • 35 CAN interface 2 firmware's major
  • 36 CAN interface 2 firmware's minor

NOTE : All values are in hexadecimal. To display the value in decimal use cout << std::hex << YourValue. std:hex is in ios header file.

Parameters
ResponseAn array of size CODE_VERSION_COUNT that contains every available version of the robotical arm.

int GetPositionCurrentActuators ( float  Response[POSITION_CURRENT_COUNT])

This function get the position and the current of all actuators. Values from index 0 to index 5 represents the position in degrees of actuator #1(near the base) to actuator #6(the wrist). The last 6 values are the current of the actuator #1 to actuator #6.

Parameters
ResponseAn array of size POSITION_CURRENT_COUNT containing the position and current values.

Here is the caller graph for this function:

int InitAPI ( )

This function initialises the API. It is the first function you call if you want the rest of the library.

Returns
  • NO_ERROR_KINOVA if operation is a success
  • ERROR_LOAD_COMM_DLL if unable to load the communication layer
  • ERROR_INIT_COMM_METHOD if unable to load the InitComm function from communication layer
  • ERROR_CLOSE_METHOD if unable to load the Close function from communication layer
  • ERROR_GET_DEVICE_COUNT_METHOD if unable to load the GetDeviceCount function from communication layer
  • ERROR_SEND_PACKET_METHOD if unable to load the SendPacket function from communication layer
  • ERROR_SET_ACTIVE_DEVICE_METHOD if unable to load the SetActiveDevice function from communication layer
  • ERROR_GET_DEVICES_LIST_METHOD if unable to load the GetDevices function from communication layer

Definition at line 458 of file Kinova.API.UsbCommandLayerUbuntu.cpp.

460  int result = NO_ERROR_KINOVA;

462  //If the API is not initialized.
463  if(!m_APIIsInit)
464  {

int RefresDevicesList ( )

This function refresh the devices list connected on the USB bus.

Returns
  • NO_ERROR_KINOVA if operation is a success
  • -1 Input/output error.
  • -2 Invalid parameter.
  • -3 Access denied (insufficient permissions)
  • -4 No such device (it may have been disconnected)
  • -5 Entity not found.
  • -6 Resource busy.
  • -7 Operation timed out.
  • -8 Overflow.
  • -9 Pipe error.
  • -10 System call interrupted (perhaps due to signal)
  • -11 Insufficient memory.
  • -12 Operation not supported or unimplemented on this platform.
  • -99 Other error.

Here is the call graph for this function:

int RunGravityZEstimationSequence ( ROBOT_TYPE  type,
double  OptimalzParam[OPTIMAL_Z_PARAM_SIZE] 
)

This function is used to run a sequence to estimate the optimal gravity parameters when the robot is standing (Z).

The arm must be in Trajectory-Position mode before to launch the procedure.

Before using this procedure, you should make sure that the torque sensors are well calibrated. This procedure is explained in the user guide and in the Advanced Specification Guide.

When the program is launched, the robot will execute a trajectory. The user must remain alert and turn off the robot if something wrong occurs (for example if the robot collides with an object). When the program ends, it will output the parameters in the console and in a text file named “ParametersOptimal_Z.txt” in the program folder. These parameters can then be sent as input to the function SetOptimalZParam().

Parameters
typeThe robot type
OptimalzParamThe result of the sequence
Warning
Do not use this function if you don't know what you are doing or you just want to give it a try. Only use it if you are familiar the concept of torque control

int SendAngularTorqueCommand ( float  Command[COMMAND_SIZE])

This function is used to send torque commands to the actuators. The torque command must be sent at least every “250 ms” (this value can be configured) otherwise the command will be set to zero (as a safety feature).

Parameters
CommandThe torque command
Warning
Do not use this function if you don't know what you are doing or you just want to give it a try. Only use it if you are familiar the concept of torque control

int SendCartesianForceCommand ( float  Command[COMMAND_SIZE])

This function is used to send Cartesian force commands to the robot. The force command must be sent at least every “250 ms” (this value can be configured) otherwise the command will be set to zero (as a safety feauture). In this first implementation, the force command is in open loop: the torque is fed to the following equation and the resulting torque is sent to the actuators.

In a future release, the Force command will be in closed-loop.

Parameters
CommandThe force command
Warning
Do not use this function if you don't know what you are doing or you just want to give it a try. Only use it if you are familiar the concept of torque control

int SendJoystickCommand ( JoystickCommand  joystickCommand)

This function sends a virtual joystick command to the robotical arm. the behaviour of the robotical arm is determined by the the control mapping associated with the API. (index 2) In the example, we assume that the robotical arm use the default mapping of the API and that it is in mode B0(Joystick translation). Assuming that, the robotical arm should move along the Z axis.

Parameters
joystickCommandThe command that you need to send to the robotical arm.

int SetActiveDevice ( KinovaDevice  device)

This function set the current active device. The active device is the device that will receive the command send by this API. If no active device is set, the first one discovered is the default active device.

Returns
  • NO_ERROR_KINOVA if operation is a success
  • ERROR_API_NOT_INITIALIZED if the API has not been initialized

int SetActuatorPIDFilter ( int  ActuatorAdress,
float  commandFilter,
float  dFilter,
float  errorFilter 
)

This function sets a PID filter value on a specific actuator. Mainly used for calibration.

Warning
Do not use this function if you don't know what you are doing!!!
Parameters
ActuatorAdressAddress of the actuator you want to calibrate. Default address are: actuator 1 = 16, actuator 2 = 17, actuator 3 = 18, ...
commandFilterLow pass filter on the command. This is the cut-off frequency (RAD / s). (Suggested range [0, 1000])
dFilterLow pass filter on the error derivative. This is the cut-off frequency (RAD / s). (Suggested range [0, 1000])
errorFilterLow pass filter on the error. This is the cut-off frequency (RAD / s). (Suggested range [0, 1000])

int SetGravityManualInputParam ( float  Command[GRAVITY_PARAM_SIZE])

This function is used to set the gravity parameters using the manual mode. For Mico and Jaco, the input is a vector of 42 float. The parameters are: [m1,m2,m3,m4,m5,m6,x1,x2,x3,x4,x5,x6,y1,y2,y3,y4,y5,y6,z1,z2,z3,z4,z5,z6] where m is the links mass, and x,y,z the links center of mass position.

The parameters will reset to default values every time the robotic arm is rebooted.

Parameters
CommandGravity parameters
Warning
For safety issues, the user should not use this function while in Torque control mode and should be in Trajectory-Position control before changing the parameters. Otherwise, for example if there is an error in one parameter, it could result in high velocity motions of the arm.

int SetGravityPayload ( float  Command[GRAVITY_PAYLOAD_SIZE])

This function is used to set the payload gravity parameters. The input is a vector of 4 float : GravityPayload = [pm, px, py, pz].

The parameter pm is the payload mass while px, py, pz are the payload center of mass position measured from the end-effector frame.

The parameters will reset to default values every time the robotic arm is rebooted.

Parameters
CommandThe payload parameters
Warning
For safety issues, the user should not use this function while in Torque control mode and should be in Trajectory-Position control before changing the parameters. Otherwise, for example if there is an error in one parameter, it could result in high velocity motions of the arm.

Here is the call graph for this function:

int SetGravityType ( GRAVITY_TYPE  type)

This function is used to set the gravity type: MANUAL_INPUT or OPTIMAL. The Manual mode is used by default and consists of specifying each robot link mass and center of mass. Default parameters are provided and can be changed with the function SetManualInputParam(). The second option is the optimal mode where the gravity parameters are accurately estimated by placing the robot in various positions. The precision of the Optimal mode is normally 3 times better than the manual mode. These parameters can be set with the function SetOptimalZParam (). The function RunGravityZEstimationSequence() will run a sequence of points in order to identify the gravity parameters and will output the parameters to send with the function SetOptimalZParam (). For now, this mode only works when the robot is standing (G = [0;0;-9.81]).

The parameters will reset to default values every time the robotic arm is rebooted.

Parameters
typeThe gravity type
Warning
For safety issues, the user should not use this function while in Torque control mode and should be in Trajectory-Position control before changing the parameters. Otherwise, for example if there is an error in one parameter, it could result in high velocity motions of the arm.

int SetPositionLimitDistance ( float  Command[COMMAND_SIZE])

This function sets the delta position over an actuator position limit where the virtual wall begins. The parameters will reset to default values every time the robotic arm is rebooted.

Parameters
CommandThe gain of each actuator.
Warning
These functions should only be used by advanced users. The user should be very cautious and be ready to turn off the robot if a problem occurs. The user should quit torque control mode and be in Trajectory-Position control mode before using theses functions. Do not use these functions if you don't know what you are doing.

Here is the call graph for this function:

int SetSwitchThreshold ( float  Command[COMMAND_SIZE])

When switching from position to torque control, the controller verifies if the torque command is close to the actual measured torque (as a safety feature to prevent high velocity motions if it is not the case). This function can be used to change the threshold over which the switching to torque mode is rejected. Default parameters can be found in the torque control documentation page under the section “Default parameters”. The parameters will reset to default values every time the robotic arm is rebooted.

Parameters
CommandThe torque switch threshold of each actuator.

int SetTorqueActuatorDamping ( float  Command[COMMAND_SIZE])

This function is used to set the actuators damping gain. This can be used to stabilize the system in some situations. The values must be over or equal to zero and are typically within 0-2. The maximum allowed damping can be set with the function SetTorqueDampingMax(). Default parameters can be found in the torque control documentation page under the section “Default parameters”. The parameters will reset to default values every time the robotic arm is rebooted.

Parameters
CommandThe damping of each actuator.

This function is used to specify the Torque Control Mode (Direct torque control or impedance control).

Parameters
Thesub type of torque control
Warning
Do not use this function if you don't know what you are doing or you just want to give it a try. Only use it if you are familiar the concept of torque control

This function is used to specify the Torque Control Mode (Direct torque control or impedance control). The options are DIRECTTORQUE, IMPEDANCE ANGULAR and IMPEDANCECARTESIAN.

Here is the call graph for this function:

int SetTorqueInactivityType ( int  type)

This function manages the torque inactivity time option. If not torque command is sent after a given time (250ms by default), the controller will take an action: (0): The robot will return in position mode (1): The torque commands will be set to zero. By default, option (1) is set for Kinova classic robots (Jaco2 and Mico) while option (0) is set for generic mode.

Advanced Configurations (for advanced users only): These functions should only be used by advanced users. The user should be very cautious and be ready to turn off the robot if a problem occurs. The user should quit torque control mode and be in Trajectory-Position control mode before using theses functions.

Parameters
typeThe inactivity type
Warning
Do not use these functions if you don't know what you are doing.

Here is the call graph for this function:

int SetTorqueRobotProtection ( int  protectionLevel)

This function is used to activate/deactivate the robot protection zone. There are several situations where the robot can come in contact with itself. To prevent collisions that could damage the robot, a basic robot protection zone covering the majority of collisions is implemented. In a first zone around the robot’s base, the damping is increased to reduce the robot velocity. If the end-effector reaches a second smaller zone around the robot’s base, the robot will stop and return in position control. The possible values are 0, 1 and 2. 0: The protection is deactivated 1: There is some damping when the effector enter the protected zone 2: There is some damping when the effector enters the protected zone and if the effector continues in that direction, the robot will switch back in position mode.

Parameters
protectionLevelThe protection level
Warning
Do not use this function if you don't know what you are doing or you just want to give it a try. Only use it if you are familiar the concept of torque control

Here is the call graph for this function:

int SetTorqueSafetyFactor ( float  factor)

This function is a safety feature used to specify the velocity threshold over which the robot will stop and return to position control. This is a safety feature to prevent the arm to perform undesired and dangerous motions when implementing or using a program. The value varies between 0 and 1. A value of “0.1” means that the safety will trigger if an actuator reaches 10% of its maximal speed. If a value of “1” is set, the safety feature is disabled. The user must be very cautious if he chooses to increase the safety factor.

Parameters
Thetype of control
Warning
Do not use this function if you don't know what you are doing or you just want to give it a try. Only use it if you are familiar the concept of torque control

int SetTorqueVibrationController ( float  level)

This function is used to set the vibration observer/controller level. In different situations, for example when interacting with a stiff environment, vibrations may occur. The vibration observer/controller is implemented to eliminate these vibrations. The input value varies between 0 and 1. A value of “0” means that the feature is deactivated and a value of “1” means that the Vibration Observer/Controller is set to its maximal level. The observer analyzes all actuators velocity signal. If the velocity signal frequency and amplitude is too high, the controller will reduce the control gains thus reducing the vibrations.

Parameters
levelVibration control level.
Warning
Do not use this function if you don't know what you are doing or you just want to give it a try. Only use it if you are familiar the concept of torque control

Here is the call graph for this function:

int ValidateCartesianTransition ( unsigned int &  Validation)

This function verify that your actual position is a valid cartesian position. It validates that the IK has a solution for your actual position.

Parameters
Validation1 means the position is valid, 0 means it is not.
Returns
  • NO_ERROR_KINOVA if operation is a success
  • ERROR_API_NOT_INITIALIZED if the API has not been initialized. To initialize it, call the InitAPI() function.
